    <annotation>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Cutt yo[u]r Coate according to yo[u]r Cloth. Euery man knowith best, where his
                    shooe pinchith him.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Alexander, si fuisset Parmenio, procederet vt Parmenio. Metiri se quemq[ue] suo modulo, ac pede, 
                    justum est, ait Horatius.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Alexander the Great"/>
                    <person name="Parmenion"/>
                    <person name="Horace"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Alexander, if he would be Parmenion, would proceed as Parmenion. Horace says 'it is just that every men is measured by his own model and standard.'</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>The place, A mighty frend, &amp; parlous Enemy.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>(Vires duoru[m] Incomparabiliu[m] Impp[eratorum].</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Alexandri, et Ca[e]saris. Tantu[m] potest Assuetudo; Callidè instructa.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Alexander the Great"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>    
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The strength of two incomparable emperors. Of Alexander and Caesar. So potent experience, having been instructed skillfully, can [be]. </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Qua[e] breui finem assegunt[u]r, viribus maioribus indigent. Cardano sa[e]pè: de Subtil. 206.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Girolamo Cardano"/>
                    <book title="De subtilitate"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Things which are small pursue the end, they require greater men. Frequently in Cardano's 'De subtilitate', p. 206.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Hùc Dituuij Strategema.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Here the stratagem of Dituvius.</translation> <!--JG: No clue abt Dituvius-->
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="Fabius Maximus; Cunctator" hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Fabius Cunctator, sapientissimus Imperator.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Fabius Maximus"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Cunctator" type="straight"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Fabius Maximus, a most wise general.</translation> 
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>A wisemans first Cautel, to Prouide for his own defences, before he attempt to offend other.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="Fabius Maximus; Cunctator" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>" Etia[m] Ca[e]sar, cum callido hoste egit cautiùs.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Even Caesar acted carefully with a cunning enemy.</translation> 
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>" principaliu[m] partiu[m], Cura, et Munitio principalis.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The watchfulness and fortification of the principal parts.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>(Iis armis, modisq[ue] pugnandum maxime, in quibus vires maxima[e]: Vt i[nfr]a, in Regulis Vegetij. Nosce teipsum: et rarò Vincêris.)</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Vegetius"/>
                    <internal_ref>
                        <target ref="HoughtonSTC11402:earbm_stc_11402_0226" text="i[nfr]a"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>One must fight chiefly with those arms, in which the greatest strengths [are]. As below, in the rules of Vegetius.
                Know yourself, and you are rarely beaten.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
                    <marginalia_text>Sieges, &amp; assaults, require more labour, time &amp; other cost.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="fyghte in playne battayle" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
                    <marginalia_text>Aperto Marte.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>In open battle.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
